        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/conveyor-types/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Conveyor Types</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Vertical Reciprocating Conveyors</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Vertical Reciprocating Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Vertical Reciprocating Conveyors (VRCs)
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A vertical reciprocating conveyor (VRC) lifts materials between two or more levels on a guided carriage or platform. VRCs are classified as conveyors under ASME B20.1 — not elevators — which simplifies code compliance, reduces installation cost, and shortens permitting timelines compared to freight elevators. VRCs handle loads from 500 lbs to over 20,000 lbs and serve as the standard vertical transport solution for mezzanine-to-floor transfers in packaging, distribution, and manufacturing facilities.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- VRC Types -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">VRC Types</div>
      <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Four VRC <span class="text-accent">Configurations</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Mechanical (Chain/Cable) VRC</h3>
        <p>Mechanical VRCs use roller chains or wire rope cables wound around a drum or driven by sprockets to raise and lower the carriage. An electric gearmotor provides the drive force. Mechanical VRCs offer the widest capacity range (500-20,000 lbs), fastest travel speeds (typically 20-40 FPM), and serve the broadest application base. PFlow Industries and Wildeck are leading mechanical VRC manufacturers. Four-post designs provide the greatest stability for heavy loads.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Hydraulic VRC</h3>
        <p>Hydraulic VRCs use hydraulic cylinders to lift the carriage. A hydraulic power unit (pump, reservoir, and valves) pressurizes hydraulic fluid that extends the cylinder. Hydraulic VRCs provide smooth, controlled motion and handle heavy loads (up to 10,000+ lbs). Travel height is limited by cylinder stroke length — typically up to 20-25 feet. Hydraulic VRCs suit applications requiring precise speed control and soft start/stop motion. Autoquip and Pflow manufacture hydraulic VRC platforms.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Autoquip max hydraulic VRC travel height -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Straddle VRC</h3>
        <p>Straddle VRCs use two vertical mast columns with a carriage that travels between them. The mast straddles one or two sides of the platform opening. Straddle designs provide clear access from multiple sides for fork truck loading or conveyor infeed/outfeed. They suit applications where the VRC must be approached from the front and one or both sides simultaneously.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Cantilever VRC</h3>
        <p>Cantilever VRCs use a single mast column with the carriage extending outward like a shelf. The platform is supported from one side only. Cantilever designs provide three-sided access to the platform and suit applications with tight floor space. Load capacity is lower than four-post designs because the single-mast structure must resist the tilting moment of off-center loads. Cantilever VRCs typically handle 500-4,000 lbs.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- VRC vs Freight Elevator -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="comparison-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">VRC vs Elevator</div>
      <h2 id="comparison-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        VRC vs Freight Elevator vs <span class="text-accent">Spiral Conveyor</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto -mx-4 px-4">
        <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse min-w-[750px]">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b-2 border-ink">
              <th class="font-display text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Feature</th>
              <th class="font-display text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">VRC</th>
              <th class="font-display text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Freight Elevator</th>
              <th class="font-display text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Spiral Conveyor</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Carries People?</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">No (materials only)</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Yes (materials + people)</td>
              <td class="py-3">No (materials only)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Governing Code</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">ASME B20.1 (conveyor)</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">ASME A17.1 (elevator)</td>
              <td class="py-3">ASME B20.1 (conveyor)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Load Capacity</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">500-20,000 lbs</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">2,000-20,000+ lbs</td>
