  <!-- Specifications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="specs-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Specifications</div>
      <h2 id="specs-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        VRC <span class="text-accent">Specification Ranges</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>VRC specifications vary widely based on type and application. Typical ranges across PFlow, Wildeck, and Autoquip product lines:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Load capacity:</strong> 500-20,000 lbs (standard), up to 100,000 lbs (custom heavy-duty)</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Travel speed:</strong> 20-40 FPM (standard), up to 100 FPM (high-speed)</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Travel height:</strong> 5-100+ feet (mechanical), 5-25 feet (hydraulic)</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Platform size:</strong> 3' x 3' (minimum) to 12' x 12' (large pallet/cart)</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Number of stops:</strong> 2-6 levels</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Power:</strong> 208-480V three-phase (mechanical), hydraulic power unit (hydraulic)</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Drive types:</strong> Chain-driven, cable-driven, hydraulic cylinder</li>
        </ul>
        <!-- VERIFY: PFlow max capacity and max travel height specifications -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Safety Codes -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="safety-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Safety & Codes</div>
      <h2 id="safety-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        VRC Safety Standards and <span class="text-accent">Code Requirements</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">ASME B20.1 Section 3008</h3>
        <p>ASME B20.1 is the primary safety standard governing VRCs. Section 3008 specifically addresses vertical reciprocating conveyors. Key requirements include full guarding of the carriage path at every accessible level, interlocked access gates that prevent VRC operation unless all gates are closed, upper and lower travel limit switches, emergency stop buttons accessible from each level, slack chain/cable detection devices, and overload protection.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Building Code Requirements</h3>
        <p>The International Building Code (IBC) recognizes VRCs as conveyors, not elevators, provided they comply with ASME B20.1 and do not carry people. The VRC shaft opening between floors may require fire-rated enclosures or sprinkler protection depending on the building's fire code classification. Consult your local authority having jurisdiction (AHJ) for specific requirements.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Key Safety Features</h3>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Interlocked gates:</strong> Every access point (loading/unloading level) has a gate that must be closed and locked before the VRC operates. Interlock circuits prevent bypassing.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Overtravel limits:</strong> Redundant limit switches stop the carriage if it overtravel past the upper or lower stop position.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Slack chain/cable detection:</strong> Sensors detect if lifting chains or cables go slack (indicating a broken chain or obstruction). The VRC stops immediately.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Emergency stops:</strong> E-stop buttons at each level and on the control panel. Red mushroom-head style per NFPA 79.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Velocity fuse (hydraulic):</strong> Hydraulic VRCs include a velocity fuse that stops the carriage if it descends faster than normal operating speed, preventing freefall in case of hydraulic line failure.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">VRC Cannot Carry People</h3>
        <p>VRCs are classified as material-only conveyors. They cannot carry people under any circumstance. Signage must clearly state "NOT FOR PERSONNEL USE" or equivalent. If your application requires lifting both materials and people, you must install a freight elevator under ASME A17.1. This distinction is the fundamental difference between VRC and elevator classification.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        VRC <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Mezzanine material transport:</strong> The most common VRC application. VRCs lift pallets, cases, and totes between the ground floor and mezzanine pick modules in distribution centers and warehouses. <a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">CDLR conveyors</a> feed pallets onto the VRC platform at the lower level and receive them at the upper level.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Multi-level <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">packaging facilities</a>:</strong> Packaging plants with production on one floor and warehousing on another use VRCs to move cased goods and pallets between levels. The VRC integrates with horizontal <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyor</a> systems via <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">transfer conveyors</a> at each level.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink"><a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Food and beverage:</a></strong> <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Sanitary stainless steel</a> VRCs move product between processing floors and packaging areas. Food-grade VRCs use washdown-rated components and sealed enclosures to maintain hygienic conditions.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Manufacturing:</strong> VRCs move raw materials from receiving docks to elevated production floors and return finished goods to ground-level shipping. Heavy-duty VRCs (6,000-20,000 lbs) handle steel coils, engine assemblies, and fabricated sub-assemblies in automotive and industrial manufacturing.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Retail distribution:</strong> Multi-level retail distribution centers use VRCs to move merchandise between receiving, pick floors, and shipping levels. <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyor</a> systems on each level connect to VRCs via powered <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation zones</a> that stage product for lift cycles.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">When to choose a VRC over a spiral:</strong> VRCs suit batch-mode applications where throughput of 10-20 loads per hour is sufficient, loads are heavy (pallets, carts), or the lift height exceeds 40 feet. Spiral conveyors suit continuous-flow applications with lightweight products (under 75 lbs) and moderate lift heights. The VRC's batch cycle is the key trade-off — it lifts one load at a time, while spirals provide uninterrupted flow.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Selection Criteria -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="selection-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Guide</div>
      <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How to Specify a <span class="text-accent">VRC</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>VRC specification requires defining these key parameters:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Load weight and size:</strong> Maximum load weight, platform dimensions needed (width x depth x height clearance), and whether the load is a pallet, cart, tote, or mixed.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Travel height:</strong> Floor-to-floor distance between the lowest and highest stop. Include any below-grade pit or overhead clearance constraints.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Number of stops:</strong> Two-stop (ground + mezzanine) is the most common. Multi-stop VRCs serve 3-6 levels.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Throughput requirement:</strong> Loads per hour required. Calculate cycle time: travel time (up + down) + load time + unload time + gate open/close time. Divide 60 minutes by cycle time to get max loads per hour.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Loading method:</strong> Fork truck, hand pallet jack, powered <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor</a>, or manual cart push. Conveyor-fed VRCs integrate with horizontal <a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">CDLR</a> or <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/powered/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">powered roller</a> lines for automated loading/unloading.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Environment:</strong> Indoor/outdoor, temperature range, washdown, and hazardous area classification affect material selection and component ratings.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Code jurisdiction:</strong> Confirm local AHJ requirements for VRC installations. Some jurisdictions require permits, inspections, or registrations beyond ASME B20.1.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>See the <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a> for VRC pricing factors. Request quotes from at least two VRC manufacturers (PFlow, Wildeck, Autoquip) to compare options. <a href="/resources/automated-conveyor-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">System integrators</a> can design the complete horizontal + vertical conveyor system as a turnkey project.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Manufacturers -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="mfg-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Manufacturers</div>
      <h2 id="mfg-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Leading VRC <span class="text-accent">Manufacturers</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">PFlow Industries</strong> — Milwaukee, WI. Largest dedicated VRC manufacturer in North America. Mechanical chain-driven VRCs with capacities from 500 to 100,000 lbs.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Wildeck</strong> — Waukesha, WI. VRCs, mezzanines, and vertical lifts. Mechanical and hydraulic models from 500 to 20,000 lbs.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Autoquip</strong> — Guthrie, OK. Hydraulic and mechanical VRCs and scissor lifts from 500 to 20,000 lbs.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Pallet Runner</strong> — VRC integration with automated pallet conveyor systems.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Dematic / Intelligrated</strong> — System integrators who specify and integrate VRCs from component manufacturers into complete <a href="/resources/automated-conveyor-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">automated conveyor systems</a>.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
